#1 Anemia, rectal versus vaginal bleeding
#2 Thickened endometrium with enlarged uterus
#3 Distal sigmoid, rectal thickness
#4 Primary endometrial versus colorectal cancer
Patient may have advanced stage endometrial cancer with involvement of the distal sigmoid and rectum.  At the same time, it can be colorectal primary.  From a gynecological point of view, patient is not a good surgical candidate based on her age, poor nutritional status, and the advanced appearance of the disease.  We do not have a diagnosis at this point.  It appears like Colorectal Surgery is planning to take this patient for a sigmoidoscopy/colonoscopy to get a tissue diagnosis.  If patient goes to the OR, we will be happy to perform a hysteroscopy and D&C and do not proceed.  I have staffed this case with Dr. Arnold who is operating at De Paul County Memorial Hospital today.  I tried to contact the primary service.  They are busy in the OR.  I am able to reached at GYN Service Chief pager 734-962-15525.  This plan was communicated to the patient.

[end section id="20112"]

[start section id="20101"]

Dr. Stanford R. Norton, Colon & Rectal Surgery.

